meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzWarin was born about 1119, in Shropshire, England, his father, Sir Fulk \"The Bold\" FitzWarin de Metz, was 41 and his mother, Maud Peverell, was 45. He married Unknown in 1149, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1172, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1119–about 1172":"umbes 1119–umbes 1172","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1113–1155":"1113–1155","1115–1171":"1115–1171","1119–1172":"1119–1172","1146–Female":"1146–Surnud","1142–1205":"1142–1205","1079–1168":"1079–1168","1075–1178":"1075–1178","about 1172":"umbes 1172","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","ABT 1107":"umbes 1107","1172":"1172","1171":"1171","1205":"1205","1149":"1149","1115":"1115","about 1119":"umbes 1119","1168":"1168","1113":"1113","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1079":"1079","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","about 1142":"umbes 1142","1119":"1119","Whittington, Shropshire, England":"Whittington, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bramley, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bramley, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burwardsley Manor, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1119–about 1172":"noin 1119–noin 1172","1100–1146":"1100–1146","1113–1155":"1113–1155","1115–1171":"1115–1171","1119–1